> Seitan, a wheat-based Japanese protein, lends heartiness to this vegetarian Bolognese. A touch of chili flakes gives this homemade tomato sauce an extra kick. Finished with nutty Parmesan, this is winter comfort food at its finest.

== Prep ==

Bring a large #pot of water to boil with a large pinch of @salt{pinch}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @shallot{2%ounces}. Finely chop the @parsley{1/4%ounce}(chopped), reserving a few leaves for garnish.

Add the @fettuccine{6%ounces} to the boiling water and cook for ~{9-11%minutes}, until al dente. Drain, reserving 1 cup pasta water.

== Bolognese ==

Start the "bolognese": Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in a large #pan over medium heat. Add the shallots and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon}(to taste, we used ¼ teaspoon) and cook, tossing, for ~{3-5%minutes}, until softened. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Warm the seitan: Add the @seitan crumbles{8%ounces} to the pan and break up into pieces with a #wooden spoon. Add the garlic, @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%teaspoon}, and the chopped parsley to the pan and cook another ~{1%minute}, until fragrant.

Finish the bolognese: Add the @crushed tomatoes{1%12oz can}, @veggie stock concentrate{1%sachet}, and 1 cup water to the pan. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer for ~{5-10%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Depending on the sweetness of your tomatoes, you may want to add up to 1 teaspoon sugar to the sauce for balance.

Add the drained tagliatelle, half the @parmesan cheese{1%ounce}(grated), and a splash of pasta water into the pan and toss to thoroughly combine.

== Finish ==

Divide the dish between #bowls{}, then garnish with the reserved parsley and the remaining Parmesan cheese. Enjoy!